{
  "analysis": "The terminal output keeps getting truncated because too many disassembly chunks are printed at once. Also python3 is not available. We need a more controlled approach: dump disassembly with no raw bytes into a file, then view small line ranges from that file. We also need a way to decode float constants; we can use a small C helper compiled with gcc since python3 is missing.",
  "plan": "First, create a compact disassembly file without raw instruction bytes. Then find line numbers for key functions and print main in small ranges. Also write and compile a tiny C helper that reads /app/mystery and prints the float values at the relevant virtual addresses, using readelf program header offset mapping. This will give us exact constants and code in digestible pieces.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/mtest && objdump -d --no-show-raw-insn /app/mystery > disasm2.txt 2>&1 && grep -n '<main>:<trace>:<sphere_intersect>:<plane_intersect>:<sky_color>:<write_image>:<allocate_image>:<vector_normalize>:<vector_dot>:' disasm2.txt\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/mtest && grep -nE '<main>:|<trace>:|<sphere_intersect>:|<plane_intersect>:|<sky_color>:|<write_image>:|<allocate_image>:|<vector_normalize>:|<vector_dot>:' disasm2.txt\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}
